          "input": {
            "content": "# Ember — Resilient Delay-Tolerant Messaging\n\n**A distributed, end-to-end encrypted messaging system built for network disruption.**\n\nEmber is a proof-of-concept messenger designed to work reliably in challenging network conditions — during outages, across intermittent connections, and over constrained transports like LoRa or BLE. It uses stateless encryption (no session state), automatic peer discovery, and a hybrid transport architecture to deliver messages even when traditional messaging systems fail.\n\n> 🚧 **Experimental — under heavy development.** This project is an experiment in AI-driven software development. The vast majority of the code, tests, and documentation were written by AI (Claude Code, Codex, GitHub Copilot, OpenCode). Humans direct architecture, priorities, and design decisions, but have not reviewed most of the code line-by-line. Treat this accordingly — there will be bugs, rough edges, and things that don't work. Use at your own risk.\n\n## Features\n\n- **Stateless encryption** — No session keys, no prekeys, no forward secrecy compromise. Messages work independently, even if delivered out of order or months late.\n- **Hybrid transport** — HTTP mailboxes (stable), MQTT (broadcast), mDNS/LAN (direct P2P), with future support for LoRa, Meshtastic, and BLE.\n- **Automatic LAN discovery** — Find and verify peers on local networks without manual configuration using mDNS/Bonjour.\n- **Tiered delivery** — Three-phase delivery strategy with configurable quorum: race ephemeral targets, require quorum from stable relays, fire-and-forget to constrained transports.\n- **Merkle DAG ordering** — Causal message ordering and gap detection without a central sequencer.\n- **Sneakernet support** — Export/import `.ember` bundle files for air-gapped message transfer.\n- **DTN-first design** — Every design choice prioritizes Delay-Tolerant Networking over low latency.\n\n## Current Status: v0.5 (Sneakernet Export)\n\nEmber is in the proof-of-concept phase. Core features implemented:\n\n- ✅ Stateless encryption (Session V1-style MIK)\n- ✅ HTTP mailbox transport with pagination\n- ✅ MQTT broadcast transport\n- ✅ mDNS/LAN peer discovery with identity verification\n- ✅ Tiered delivery system with outbox retry\n- ✅ Merkle DAG for message ordering\n- ✅ Tombstones for delivery receipts and cache clearing\n- ✅ Sneakernet bundle export/import\n- ✅ TUI client with embedded relay capability\n\nSee [ROADMAP.md](ROADMAP.md) for upcoming features and [WHITEPAPER.md](WHITEPAPER.md) for protocol details.\n\n## Quick Start\n\n### Prerequisites\n\n- Rust 1.75+ (edition 2021)\n- SQLite 3 (bundled via `rusqlite`)\n\n### Build from Source\n\n```bash\n# Clone the repository\ngit clone https://github.com/leon0399/ember.git\ncd ember\n\n# Build all binaries\ncargo build --release\n\n# Binaries will be in target/release/\n# - client: TUI client with embedded relay\n# - node: Standalone mailbox server\n```\n\n### Run a Local Network\n\n**Terminal 1 — Start a mailbox node:**\n```bash\ncargo run --bin node -- --port 3000\n```\n\n**Terminal 2 — Start first client (Alice):**\n```bash\ncargo run --bin client\n```\n\n**Terminal 3 — Start second client (Bob):**\n```bash\ncargo run --bin client\n```\n\nIn the TUI:\n1. Create a new identity (if first run)\n2. Add a contact using their Public ID\n3. Select the contact and start messaging\n\nMessages will automatically route through the local mailbox node at `http://127.0.0.1:3000`.\n\n### Test LAN Discovery\n\nIf both clients have embedded relay enabled and are on the same network:\n\n1. Enable LAN discovery in config: `lan_discovery.enabled = true`\n2. Bind embedded HTTP server: `embedded_node.http_bind = \"0.0.0.0:0\"` (random port)\n3. Restart clients — they'll discover each other automatically via mDNS\n\nDirect P2P messages will bypass the mailbox node entirely.\n\n## Architecture\n\nEmber uses a modular Rust workspace:\n\n```\ncrates/\n├── ember-identity      # X25519/XEdDSA identity management\n├── ember-encryption    # Stateless encryption (MIK-based)\n├── ember-message       # Wire formats (OuterEnvelope, InnerEnvelope, Tombstone, DAG)\n├── ember-transport     # Transport abstraction (HTTP, MQTT, coordinator)\n├── ember-storage       # SQLite persistence (contacts, messages, outbox)\n├── ember-outbox        # Tiered delivery with retry policies\n├── ember-node-core     # Shared mailbox/relay logic\n├── ember-discovery     # mDNS/LAN peer discovery\n├── ember-config        # Layered configuration (CLI > env > file > defaults)\n├── ember-contact       # Contact management with trust levels\n├── ember-bundle        # Sneakernet bundle format\n└── ember-core          # High-level Client API\n\napps/\n├── client/            # TUI client (ratatui) with embedded relay\n└── node/              # Standalone mailbox server (Axum)\n```\n\n## Configuration\n\nBoth binaries support layered configuration:\n\n- CLI arguments (highest priority)\n- Environment variables (`EMBER_*` / `EMBER_NODE_*`)\n- Config file (`~/.config/ember/config.toml` / `node.toml`)\n- Defaults (lowest priority)\n\nSee `apps/client/config.example.toml` and `apps/node/config.example.toml` for all options.\n\n## Documentation\n\n- **[WHITEPAPER.md](WHITEPAPER.md)** — Protocol specification, cryptography, wire format\n- **[ROADMAP.md](ROADMAP.md)** — Release timeline and feature planning\n- **[docs/threat-model.md](docs/threat-model.md)** — Attack scenarios and mitigations\n- **[docs/tiered-delivery.md](docs/tiered-delivery.md)** — Three-tier delivery system design\n- **[docs/lan-discovery.md](docs/lan-discovery.md)** — mDNS peer discovery and verification\n\n## Security Model\n\n⚠️ **No forward secrecy in v0.5** — Ember uses stateless encryption (MIK-only) to maximize DTN tolerance. Compromise of the Master Identity Key exposes all past messages. This is an **explicit design tradeoff** for delay-tolerant networking. Forward secrecy (Async Noise Handshake V2) is planned for v1.0 as an optional upgrade path.\n\n**Other security properties:**\n- End-to-end encryption (X25519 + ChaCha20-Poly1305)\n- Message authentication (XEdDSA signatures)\n- Identity verification (challenge-response for LAN peers)\n- No plaintext message content on relays\n\nSee [docs/threat-model.md](docs/threat-model.md) for full analysis.\n\n## Development\n\n### Running Tests\n\n```bash\n# All tests (unit + integration)\ncargo test --workspace --all-features --all-targets\n\n# Specific crate\ncargo test -p ember-core\n\n# Single test\ncargo test -p ember-core test_two_client_messaging\n```\n\n### Code Quality\n\n```bash\n# Format check\ncargo fmt --all -- --check\n\n# Lint\ncargo clippy --all-targets --all-features -- -D warnings\n\n# License/dependency audit\ncargo deny check\n```\n\n### Quality Gates (enforced via workspace lints)\n\n- No `.unwrap()` or `.expect()` in library crates\n- No `todo!()`, `unimplemented!()`, `dbg!()` in merged code\n- Cognitive complexity ≤ 15 per function\n- All dependencies pass `cargo-deny` policy (GPL-3.0-or-later compatible)\n\n## Contributing\n\nEmber is in the research/prototype phase. External contributions are welcome, but expect frequent breaking changes and API instability until v1.0.\n\n**Before contributing:**\n1. Read [WHITEPAPER.md](WHITEPAPER.md) for protocol context\n2. Check [ROADMAP.md](ROADMAP.md) to avoid duplicate work\n3. Open an issue to discuss major changes\n\nCommit style: [Conventional Commits](https://www.conventionalcommits.org/) with scope when applicable:\n```\nfeat(discovery): add DHT transport fallback\nfix(encryption): handle nonce wraparound\ndocs(roadmap): update v1.0 timeline\n```\n\n## License\n\n**GPL-3.0-or-later**\n\nEmber is free software: you can redistribute it and/or modify it under the terms of the GNU General Public License as published by the Free Software Foundation, either version 3 of the License, or (at your option) any later version.\n\nSee [LICENSE](LICENSE) for full text.\n\n## Why \"Ember\"?\n\nAn ember glows quietly, surviving long after the flame has gone out. In network disruptions, when instant messaging systems go dark, Ember keeps messages alive — waiting patiently to deliver them when connectivity returns.\n\n## Acknowledgments\n\nThis project is supported by the [NLnet Foundation](https://nlnet.nl/) through the [NGI Zero Commons Fund](https://nlnet.nl/commonsfund/).\n\nEmber builds on research and inspiration from:\n- **Session** (OPTF) — Onion routing and stateless encryption\n- **Briar** — DTN messaging over Tor and local transports\n- **Meshtastic** — LoRa mesh networking\n- **Nostr** — Decentralized relay architecture\n- **Signal Protocol** — Modern E2EE messaging (studied but not adopted due to DTN incompatibility)\n\n---\n\n**Website:** [getember.chat](https://getember.chat)\n**Repository:** [github.com/leon0399/ember](https://github.com/leon0399/ember)\n**Contact:** [GitHub Issues](https://github.com/leon0399/ember/issues)\n",
